<response>None<//response>< review>
I was referred to Dr. Heidi Cough by my best friend after leaving a nightmare OB-GYN who performed my ovarian cystectomy.  Dr. Cough delivered my best friend's (1st) baby about 5 years ago.  She was very happy with Dr. Cough's service & professionalism.

I've been going to OCWMG since then.  In the last 5 years, I've only had 1 last minute cancellation because Dr. Cough was delivering a baby, which is very understandable.  I am now 22 weeks pregnant under Dr. Cough's care.  I love her positive attitiude, care to thoroughly answer my husband & my questions, her bedside manners, and her professionalism.  I suffer from anxiety disorder and yet feel very comfortable knowing that I'm in the great hands of Dr. Cough for the upcoming labor & delivery.  Saddleback Memorial is not the closest hospital to me yet the anxiety of the distance is soothed by my trust that Dr. Cough will take great care of me and the baby.

I've also seen Nurse Practitioner Carolyn Patchett and was very happy with her care.  I read some of the other reviews and disagree about the negative reviews about the office staff.  In the past 5 years, I have never met a rude or unhelpful staff member.  Every office staff member I've met or talked to on the phone has been helpful, kind, and respectful both at the Laguna Hills office and Irvine office.

One of the best services provided by OCWMG is the ability to email any questions to their nursing staff.  This is my 1st pregnancy and I have had many questions that I forget to ask during appointments or the questions come up inbetween appointments.  I simply send messages through their website and within a day or two, all my random questions and concerns are answered.  It's great!

Another great service is their after-hours care.  A few weeks ago I woke up in the middle of the night with severe pains in my abdomen.  I panicked that something was wrong with my pregnancy.  I called and explained what was going on.  The answering service tech notified the after-hour doctor and an OCWMG doctor called me back an hour later to help advise me.  The following morning a nurse called to follow-up with me.  Then later that day Dr. Cough called me to make sure I was okay and to see how the recommendations were going.  I really felt comforted and like a valued patient when the staff cared to check on me twice after.

Since I've experienced such great care with Dr. Cough & OCWMG, I have referred my mom too.  She's been with Dr. Cough for the past 5 years too.  She loves the convenience of being able to schedule her annual gynecological checkup with her mammogram & bone density scan on the same day & location.< /review>

<user_id>109336153863188176100< /user_id><name>Jane Crump</name><Date>1544990374351</Date><rating>1<//rating>< text>
This is the first time I have ever actually been inspired to follow through in writing a negative review for anyone. The only reason this pharmacy should even have a star at all is that it provides life saving medicine to people who need it, which is only because it is in fact a pharmacy. I have  been using the CVS pharmacy on 41st Ave. for about 4 years beginning with the birth of my second child. It was the natural choice as it was the only pharmacy nearby with a drive through. It is hard enough being sick, let alone dragging in 2 small children along with you. I have to say the drive through window (despite it's colossally slow wait times) remains the most positive thing about the service  of this pharmacy. Think about that: a physical structure being the best thing about a place where thousands of people come. So, why do I say this? For all the years I've been coming, I have been frustrated by incredibly long wait times whether inside or at the drive through, prescriptions not being ready even after having received text messages that they are, and then having to wait an additional 30-45 minutes for them to get those prescriptions ready, long  wait times for prescriptions to be ready after coming from the doctor's office, and waiting on hold for up to 45 minutes on one occasion to speak to someone in the department. The common complaint I have seems to be wait time. Which is what I kind of expect from a pharmacy to some degree, which is why that drive through window and the potential that I might need it when picking up a prescription has kept me coming back. Until today.
Last night I was prescribed something that I needed to start ASAP and CVS was closed so it got sent to the Walgreens on Freedom. I got to the Walgreens only to discover that they were out of both the medications I needed. Fine, it happens. They told me that I needed to ask my pharmacy to call them to transfer the prescription over to them. I got to CVS first thing this morning (to avoid the dreaded wait time), and was able to speak with someone pretty quickly (a nice change). They said it would be 15-20 minutes for the prescription to be ready ( which honestly does feel much longer - not their fault- with two kids in the car and a full blown case of Influenza A) and one of the medications was. The other wasn't showing up, so I told them what the pharmacist at Walgreens said. The tech at CVS said it would take a bit but they would call when it was ready. No problem. So when I get the call from the pharmacist she says that she called the Walgreens and was on hold for 12 minutes and no one answered so it might be faster for me to ask them to transfer it. I explained that I was there in person last night and asked them to transfer it and that I was clearly instructed that the pharmacy needed to call. Now, I have to admit that my years of frustration may have emerged a bit. She continued on to say it might be faster if I call ( did she not hear me?) To which I told her, no it would not be and that considering the hours I have collectively waited for things from them, couldn't they call back try again. Wasn't it part of what they do at the pharmacy? To which she replied she could not sit and wait on hold for a pharmacist for all that time. To which I replied that I know all about waiting on hold for pharmacists considering I've been using theirs for years. And could I please speak with their manager? Her response was that she would not continue to be verbally abused and hung up on me.
I guess I need to figure something else out for my prescription? I get that whoever I was talking to was not responsible for all of my collective frustration, and that if she was waiting on hold it would be taking her away from other customers who would then be frustrated by having to wait. I also realized that I may be overly agitated as a result of having a fever and feeling generally miserable. My frustrations have spanned years and are countless. Being hung up on is the final straw.< /text>

Terrible pharmacy.  When you call you're taken through multiple menus to get to a person.  Then you'll inevitably be put on hold for 15 min (while you're forced to listen to an awful, distorted recording the same Liberace-esque elevator music they've had on there for years).  Very nice employees who are trying their best, but honestly, go to Tom's, a very nice local pharmacy where you can talk to real people the first time you call, there's never a line of more than one or two people, and you're supporting a local business.

Also, while I'm on this rant, CVS takes up to 24 h to refill a prescription even if you need it immediately, there are always long lines, and they have little flexibility when it comes to special requests and issues. We transferred to Tom's a year ago and are very happy (the reason I'm writing this is that my doc accidentally filled a new prescription at CVS and I had to got through the whole routine all over again.  Ugh!)<//text>

<Date>1569515375190< /Date><rate>2</rate><text>Going through an omakase phase, we decided to try out a bunch of different sushi spots that offered omakase. Of course in Torrance, there are a ton!

While the sushi here at Nozomi was comparable to other places. Fish quality was good, and the variety was pretty much the same across the board. What was extremely missing here was the customer service from our sushi chef. We sat at the counter to get the full experience, and were basically ignored after we ordered. Our sushi chef didn't bother talking to us and basically avoided looking at us. Most of the time he looked off into another part of the restaurant. He wasn't busy, he just didn't want to interact with us at all. He made our sushi, put it on our plates, then went back to just standing there until we were ready for our next piece.

There are much better omakase experiences all over Torrance. The right ones where the sushi chef interacts with the customer and sees what they like, and what they don't like. The sushi we got at Nozomi wasn't special for us, and really was more of a sushi combination with he usual suspects.<//text><pictures>None< /pictures>< Response>

<user>111675655856518218213<//user><username>Christine Yabuda< /username>< date>
1569515375190</date>
< rating>
2</rating>
< text>
Going through an omakase phase, we decided to try out a bunch of different sushi spots that offered omakase. Of course in Torrance, there are a ton!

While the sushi here at Nozomi was comparable to other places. Fish quality was good, and the variety was pretty much the same across the board. What was extremely missing here was the customer service from our sushi chef. We sat at the counter to get the full experience, and were basically ignored after we ordered. Our sushi chef didn't bother talking to us and basically avoided looking at us. Most of the time he looked off into another part of the restaurant. He wasn't busy, he just didn't want to interact with us at all. He made our sushi, put it on our plates, then went back to just standing there until we were ready for our next piece.

There are much better omakase experiences all over Torrance. The right ones where the sushi chef interacts with the customer and sees what they like, and what they don't like. The sushi we got at Nozomi wasn't special for us, and really was more of a sushi combination with he usual suspects.</text>

This is a no frills sushi restaurant located in the middle of a strip mall with some of the best sushi I've had anywhere.

The fish is incredibly fresh with each fish coming from some of the best locations (Blue Fin tuna from Spain, Salmon from Scotland, Yellowtail from Japan).

Get here early to avoid the rush, sit at the sushi bar and get the Chef's special.

You can thank me later...< /Text>

<date>1403892908488< /date><resp>None<//resp><pics>None<//pics><text>As my regular readers are aware, I eat a lot of sushi; I am pretty picky about the sushi I eat and there are only two people (Song and Alex) that I go to when I want it. Unfortunately, neither of my friends is currently available so I was prepared to abstain for a while. Tanya, on the other hand was not. Tanya is an interesting case because she only recently started eating sushi and she was only familiar with Song‚Äôs fusion style of preparation. Since we knew Song was selling his business, Tanya had been talking about visiting a new sushi bar and has been looking around and asking friends for recommendations. A couple of weeks ago she picked up a Los Angeles magazine that had an article that discussed the top 15 locations for sushi in Los Angeles; one of them was Sushi Nozomi in Torrance. I took a look around their website and was slightly uncomfortable; it was apparent they are more traditional sushi than the fusion style I had introduced Tanya to so I really was not sure she was going to like it. In fact, I had so little confidence on this being a positive experience that I did not bother bringing my camera. Tanya mentioned that if nothing else we can have some sake and beer, so the worst case scenario was not all that bad.

I have frequently said that the best restaurants are in strip malls, so I wasn‚Äôt taken aback by its location. It you want a seat with a view, sit at the bar and you can see how fresh the fish is. Their hours were the typical lunch (11:30-2:00PM) then closed until dinner (5:30-10:00PM). We got there shortly after they opened for dinner and there were already people seated. They have a very long sushi bar with three chefs at the ready; they all welcomed us with ‚ÄúIrasshaimase‚Äù as we entered. It was our first time there so I was prepared to sit at the first seats but there was a ‚ÄúReserved‚Äù sign for the first 10 spots so we just walked down to the end where we met Toshi, our chef for the evening.

I explained to Toshi what Tanya was allergic to in case we ordered something that might contain shellfish or avocado. They had some predefined dinners as well as sushi and sashimi but we went with ordering a couple of rolls, the Rainbow Roll and Spicy Salmon. Even though Tanya is accustomed to the tasty sauces Song has with his rolls, these had no sauces and relied solely on the taste of the fish and rice; they were very good. I asked Toshi if he had a special roll that he had created to which I received a variation on the Cucumber Roll; at least, I think it was a variation. It was tasty and had a very nice presentation.

During the dinner I was talking with Toshi about how I had read that they had fish fresh from Tokyo on a daily basis. He told me it was true that two or three of the fish came from Tokyo, but some fish came from one country and some other fish came from somewhere else. It was obvious that he was pretty proud of the quality of the fish they served. All I know is that we will return and next time I will bring my camera.<//text>< user_name>
Beer Guy< /user_name>
<Rating>4< /Rating>< user>

<text>In a nutshell, if you need HVAC assistance, whether for repair or replacement, you can trust Bob Jenson's technicians to be honest, skilled, polite, and personable. The nitty gritty: With impeccable timing, my 20-year-old air conditioner failed during a really hot day. Since I had dealt with Bob Jenson before and was pleased with the results, I called them. Swamped with other business, Ellice scheduled John to visit us a few days later. In the meantime, I did some research and suspected that the condenser had failed, but knew that could have been just wishful thinking. When John arrived, I let him know that I had done some research and was prepared for having to replace the HVAC system. John said, "I'm not here to sell you anything. Let's see what we can do to get you back up and running." And, luckily for us, John found that it was indeed a failed condenser. He also told us that our system was in fairly good shape given its age, and that we might have up to 5 years left on it before replacement was needed. We discussed BTUs and condenser sizes and John confirmed my research, not trying to push me into considering in the future something that was more than I would need. Please do call Bob Jenson if you need help with your HVAC system. The prices are reasonable and the service is top-notch.</text>< user>

I give top ratings to Bob Jensen Air Conditioning and Heating in every category.  In particular, Marcella Gorghis in the Service Department was gracious, knowledgeable, and most helpful in taking my service request.  Then she offered me suggestions and options to get exactly what I needed to solve my air conditioning problems as quickly as possible on a hot summer day.  Nobody could have been more helpful than she was.  On the other hand, Bob Jensen AC & H installed my systems 22 years ago.  Only two times before in all those years have I needed service, a testimony to the excellent installation work as well as the excellent system they installed.  But when you do have to call for service, and you get a representative as courteous and competent as Marcella Gorghis, you know you are in good hands before the service technician even arrives.

I must also commend service technician Roy Villa for going out of his way to make certain everything was checked and informing me of things I had never noticed.  Roy patiently listened to all my thoughts and concerns before beginning his work.  My air conditioner received the repair it needed and Roy took added steps to ensure that the problem would not occur again.  But he further took steps to reassure me that all my concerns were dealt with so I can feel confident my system will last for many years to come.  No service technician could have been more efficient and competent than he was.  In the 22 years since Bob Jensen AC & H installed my systems, only two times before have I needed service. < text>
I am very pleased with our 4-year-old Fujitsu 3-zone Mini-Split heat pump system installed and serviced by Bob Jenson Air Conditioning and Heating.  The mini-split has proved to be an excellent economic addition to our 1980 starter condo.

I am also appreciative of and recommend the Bob Jenson extended warranty plan that provides for twice per year service calls.

Marcella Gorghis does an excellent job of scheduling the maintenance visits with friendly telephone calls and follow-up E-mails that provide a picture of the 100% drug free, background checked, safety and professionally trained Bob Jenson technician that is scheduled.

Today our Technician was Jeremy Zavala.  Jeremy did a very thorough and professional job in his seasonal system maintenance for cooling.  He wore booties over his shoes while working inside.

He checked each of the 3 wall units and the compressor and checked the operation of the system from the remotes.  He removed, cleaned and re-installed the filters.  He also inspected and cleaned the condensation lines and checked the 2nd floor pump operation.  He inspected the blower wheels, coils, and control boards. He checked fuses, compressor, condenser fan motor, and capacitor. He tightened both the high and low voltage connections.  Finally, he hosed off the coils of the outside compressor which had gotten dirty from the adjacent alder trees.

I highly recommend the Fujitsu Mini-split and Bob Jenson Air Conditioning and Heating.</text>

You will enjoy Aura if:
-You like spending $20 to hear the awesome setlist of a mediocre wedding DJ
-You have a strong sense of nostalgia for the sound system in your ex-boyfriends 1998 Acura Integra
-You appreciate waiting 30 minutes for your turn in a dripping wet cave of a bathroom where you are greeted with the luxury of overflowing toilets and no toilet paper
-You love a 10:1 male to female ratio where the men have both the looks of Gabriel Iglesias and the charm of Chris Brown
-You appreciate the pleasant surprise of touching surfaces that are dripping wet with mystery liquids
-You're emotionally moved by expressionless girls waving around light up sticks with all the enthusiasm and excitement of a funeral procession
-You like waiting 20-30 minutes and paying upwards of $12
for a luxury glass of Purple Drank sugar water
-You like being assaulted by overly aggressive and posessive hood rats who apparently have nothing better to do with their lives than spend $4000 on mid range liquor in the world's saddest nightclub< /Review>

<Rate>5</Rate><Review>As my car was getting some early Monday morning service, I wanted to have a healthy, relaxing breakfast (not just greasy or sugary to-go stuff).
So glad I found w/in reasonable walking distance of my dealership the Chocolate Bar Cafe, aka CB Bistro Hollywood!
Got to munch on 2 different types of savory breakfast pastries that have scrambled eggs, bacon, tomato, spinach, etc. In them.
Also got myself seated by the window to people watch and avail of their free WiFi.

< review>
Ive been there three times in one week,.. well twice as they were closed on Tuesday afternoon.  Cakes are delicate, but the Almond Croissant is mind blowing.  The Chocolate Croissant probably is too, I loved it, but was happily distracted from the Almond I ate first.  I wouldn't usually eat two in a row, one was for my partner, but the egg sandwiches I picked up at another restaurant messed up my order,.. I said "no meat, just egg and cheese, and when I got home it was just meat, no egg or cheese.  I don't eat meat, so my partner ate it and gave me his croissant.  Long story short, The Chocolate Bar must be visited at least two or three times to maintain perspective on first impressions. The key is being selective, not over doing it. Do you get what I'm saying,.. the Almond was so good, that what I really needed was to be alone with the experience.  I will return most definitely, but it will always be an exercise in moderation.  Full disclosure, if it's baked and done well, I'm there.  Just in case you thought I was over selling.</review>

<name>Victoria Voigt</name><date>1595089308855</date><Rate>3</Rate><Review>Man, I really wanted to like this place so it saddens me to have to give it three stars. I stumbled upon Ultreya after getting my tires changed around the corner. They had a great array of vegan pastries and I ended up getting one plain croissant and one chocolate croissant along with a chai tea latte. This came out to $15 which I thought was pretty expensive, but considering my favorite vegan pastry shop in Hillcrest charges $5 for a croissant, I figured it would be worth it. Oh, how wrong I was...

So let me be clear, the house-made chai tea was worth every penny as it was likely the best I have had in my life (five stars). But the pastries... oh my gosh they had to have been a day old at least (one star). Probably more like two days. I couldn't eat more than two bites of my chocolate croissant despite how hungry I was.

I always want to support vegan eateries but I felt very ripped off by this place, plus the "boss" was pretty cold and stand offish. The cashier was nice enough though.

I called Honda America and told them exactly what happened; I mentioned the other investigations into exploding sunroofs from Honda (as well as other vehicle types) and the representative told me yes, that I should schedule an appointment to have a diagnostic test completed in order for it to be considered a defect and covered by Honda. I called right away to schedule an appointment for Saturday morning and I explained that Honda America acknowledged this defect and the dealership will treat this as such. After confirming the appointment, I then received a call back saying that because it was a defect I would have to reschedule my appointment for Monday at 7am to have a manager present. I said no problem, I didn't drive anywhere over the weekend in fear of glass getting pushed around, and I showed up Monday morning at 7am. Right as I arrived, a gentleman came up to my car and so rudely interrupted and talked over me the entire time I tried explaining what happened and what Honda America said. He was unbelievably disrespectful and not only wrote me off completely, but he acted as thought I knew absolutely nothing about anything! It was ridiculous. All I was told by him, before he even looked into my sunroof, that this was not a defect, a pebble hit my car, and they will not be doing a diagnostic test as was scheduled. All he had done was take a couple pictures then walked away. I then asked to speak to a manager only to be told managers don't arrive until 9am. WHY would they tell me to come in early for a manager to be present since Honda America agreed it was a defect even though there wouldn't be any managers there until two hours later? The service rep had a terrible attitude, treated me with no regard, and talked down to me which I can only be lead to believe it was because I am a woman. I saw him interact and speak with male customers in a completely different manner than he did with me. I could not believe it. Would he have respected me more if I told him I was in the military? Just typing this out and thinking about how he treated me absolutely baffles me. He didn't even want to listen to me. I asked him to show me where the pebble would be if it had fallen through. He couldn't answer because he didn't find one. I had done my research, I wasn't asking Honda to replace my car. I was asking Honda to honor their customer service and warranty pledge and fix a defect in a car they produce. (A defect that is currently being investigated by NHTSA with countless prior incidents. I even had the documents to show all of this.) This is a known defect, backed by the NHTSA investigations. Finally, and this is the kicker, I waited two and a half hours for a manager to arrive and he quoted me almost $1000 but would "give me a discount" so I wouldn't have to use my insurance since they weren't looking into it for being a defect. Even after this discount, there was absolutely no way I was going to get my sunroof fixed at this shop. As much as I wanted Honda to honor their defect policy, I needed to get it fixed as I feared it would become dangerous for myself as well as other drivers. When I took my car to another repair shop because Pacific Honda made me feel so uncomfortable and disrespected, I was asked why I did not just go to Honda because this is a known defect, and that this shop has seen this before! I could not believe it. The repair shop said it must be because my car is a 2020 and it could be too new. I bought a brand new Honda Civic because of its reputation of quality and customer service. < review>
I found this dealership to be highly focused on upselling "extras" throughout the buying and financing process.  I felt that much of the buying process could/should have been done online, but instead required me to sit in the store for an extended period of time.  The dealership then incorrected informed me that I did not have sufficient auto insurance coverage to take the vehicle home.  When I finally got a hold of my insurance company, I learned that I did in fact have ALL of the insurance requested by the dealership.  Although I left with a new vehicle, I left disappointed in the drawn out sales/financing process that was riddled with attempts to upsell me on products and services that I do not want or need. <rate>5</rate><Review>Ryan was fantastic and really tried to understand my needs. We looked at both new and used cars, compared leases vs financing or cash, and he took me on a test drive route that safely let me open it up and test all the features. Ask for Ryan Soliman if you want someone to get you what you're actually looking for.
I settled on  a used Civic with only the options I really wanted. Their online listings are priced to sell and they didn't make me buy anything extra or add on any hidden fees! (TTL and Doc are all standard)
When working with financing, I'd really appreciate having my options presented to me to review. Instead of certifications, they reduce their prices and offer 3 levels of warranty. Even though Pacific Honda has a good record, I went for the 2 year, mid-tier warranty (covers power-train and anything else mechanical), so I have no fears about buying a used car. The optional "Karr" system is a one-time fee which lets you find your car and has an awesome remote lock/unlock, but I skipped that this time. Make sure you ask for that info as soon as you sit down with financing!
Thanks, Ryan & the Pacific Honda team. <text>Over the last few years I have had my share of bs car dealerships and shady sales people. So much that when I first contacted Pacific Honda I was already on the defensive side. I emailed an inquiry regarding a Honda accord. A sales person by the name of Joji replied to my inquiry on May 4th. He asked if he could call me. I said no, that I want to communicate through email only. ( I do this so I can reference back just in case . ) Joji respected my wishes and by May 6th we had over 30 emails going back and forth. Never once did he talk about prices ,credit scores, or push for me to come in.
One day I emailed him and his boss called me and told me Joji was off that day and he would get back to me. He didn't try to get involved or push a sale, simply a courtesy call. Later that day Joji actually replied back to my email and answered more of my questions. ON HIS DAY OFF! I thought that was pretty cool. We continued to talk and he respectfully answered all my questions,never once pushing for a sale. He told me at the beginning, when your ready then we will talk  and he kept his word. Then on May 8th I emailed him and asked if I could come and look at some cars. He said yes and I came in on May 9th. Today I took my Honda Civic into Pacific Honda to get a new Battery. I called before I went down and they said that they were not  busy so just come in whenever I want. I talked to a service advisor : Joshua  Herrera about the battery and told him about the positive connection to the battery was loose and I could not get it to tighten any more. But another option would be that they could try to put a new connector on the wire and it would only cost $80.00. That seemed better than the $450.00 for a new harness, so I told him lets do that. <Text>Very nice and no pressure sales staff.<//Text><GmapID>0x80dbff96ed549445:0xf98df63221cb3909< /GmapID><time>1606076081240</time><Pictures>None< /Pictures></record>

<Pics>None<//Pics><Response>{'time': 1598023237414, 'text': 'Patrick, we regret to hear that you had a negative experience with us, but would appreciate the chance to turn your experience around. Our manager would really like to speak with you more regarding this matter. Please reach out to Jeff Young at (858) 522-1270 or jyoung@pacifichonda.com. We look forward to hearing from you.'}< /Response>< Review>
Pacific Honda failed to satisfy our purchase experience at every turn. After letting the salesperson know that we had to leave by 6pm at 4pm (after arriving at 2pm for our scheduled appointment), we still did not complete the purchase. That was fine as Pacific Honda needed to complete recall repairs before releasing the vehicle. We completed the vast majority of paperwork and they promised the vehicle would be available the next day (Saturday) and they would call us when it was ready.

Saturday came and along about 2pm and I had not heard from them, so I called. It turns out they don't do recall repairs on the weekend, so the car wouldn't be available till Monday.

Monday comes and I receive a call from the dealership saying the car was "ready for pickup". It was about noon, so I went down during my lunch break. This was nothing but failure. They made my wife and I wait for 30 mins before talking to a person. The car WAS NOT READY. Despite a call to the contrary, they had not completed all work necessary to release the vehicle. The sales manager then had the gall to lay the blame on us when the message on my voicemail clearly said "Your car is ready for pickup." Finally, they lost our paperwork. So a trip that should have been 15 mins took 2 hours.

We then had to return for a 3rd time later in the week as they had forgotten to give us the 2nd key and the users manual. We were told upon going out of our way to pick up those items that it was our fault they had been forgotten because WE were in a rush to get out of there previously.

We were also promised that we would receive standard review of features in the car and that they would be contacting us to schedule this. It has been weeks now and we have not heard a word from Honda about this. We were specifically asked to mark on our survey that this review had been completed despite it not.

I would have given Pacific Honda one star, but the sales person Ryan was pleasant and informative. Every other part of the experience failed to meet expectations.</Review>

<Name>Okan Akdag (Mandalinan)<//Name>< text>
I and my wife are writing this feedback based on our experience with Honda Pacific, which has been difficult.

- We decided to lease a car and signed our contract with Pacific Honda, San Diego CA on October 27, 2019. We wanted to make our first brand new car lease or purchase from an experienced store so we could be guided through the process. After signing the contract, we brought our student IDs in order to benefit a $500 student discount and it was when the representative realized our visa type and said he should show it to the manager.
- It was understandable that the young representative was not familiar with the student visa, even though we informed that we are international, doing our masters and working at the same time before we signed the contract. After weeks of stressful waiting without knowing if the car was taken back or not, finally, we were told that we weren‚Äôt suitable for a leasing contract but we could buy the car.
- We agreed to buy the car, paid the $1000 difference (between leasing and purchase) on down payment and signed a new contract. We made this payment with our credit card in the Pacific Honda store with a Finance department representative. A week later, they told us we should have made the payment from a debit card instead of a credit card. We told that we already paid our credit card bill for that month and they asked for the statement, which we provided later.
- We couldn‚Äôt understand why our payment method was incorrect considering we made the payment with the finance department and they approved the credit card. However, we were fine because finally it was solved after we provided the statement and they approved. The following week, we realized our $1000 payment was refunded to our account with no explanation and we were back to where we started.
- Imagine, a customer wants to make a payment but the seller keeps making it hard. After weeks of trying hard, we finally could make the down payment and waited until January 8, when was the due date for the first payment to the bank. But, we weren‚Äôt informed about how we could make the payment because Pacific Honda was in communication with Capital One. When we called to have information about the payment process, we learned that Pacific Honda didn‚Äôt send the deal to Capital One on time, so the offer had expired.
- As we mentioned above, we specifically chose Pacific Honda based on their experience because we needed assistance through the process as a first-time purchaser. We believe, all the misfortune we had was based on a lack of knowledge or communication between the departments. Information given or action taken by a department was rejected by another department while we were never informed properly about what was the next. When we wanted to return the car, they said we cannot give it back but Honda can take it back if necessary. The amount of stress and unknown we had made us regret this purchase. Almost after 3 months, we could finalize the process by making the first payment in January and decided to write this feedback.
- We understand problems may occur during a sales process, which is okay. What we care is the way it‚Äôs handled and if the company is solution-oriented. Unfortunately, we couldn‚Äôt see this effort and the lack of communication within the company caused us a lot of time and stress. We are writing this feedback by hoping no one else has the same experience we had.

Regards,
Okan & Begum AKDAG</text>

<text>I and my wife are writing this feedback based on our experience with Honda Pacific, which has been difficult.

- We decided to lease a car and signed our contract with Pacific Honda, San Diego CA on October 27, 2019. We wanted to make our first brand new car lease or purchase from an experienced store so we could be guided through the process. After signing the contract, we brought our student IDs in order to benefit a $500 student discount and it was when the representative realized our visa type and said he should show it to the manager.
- It was understandable that the young representative was not familiar with the student visa, even though we informed that we are international, doing our masters and working at the same time before we signed the contract. After weeks of stressful waiting without knowing if the car was taken back or not, finally, we were told that we weren‚Äôt suitable for a leasing contract but we could buy the car.
- We agreed to buy the car, paid the $1000 difference (between leasing and purchase) on down payment and signed a new contract. We made this payment with our credit card in the Pacific Honda store with a Finance department representative. A week later, they told us we should have made the payment from a debit card instead of a credit card. We told that we already paid our credit card bill for that month and they asked for the statement, which we provided later.
- We couldn‚Äôt understand why our payment method was incorrect considering we made the payment with the finance department and they approved the credit card. However, we were fine because finally it was solved after we provided the statement and they approved. The following week, we realized our $1000 payment was refunded to our account with no explanation and we were back to where we started.
- Imagine, a customer wants to make a payment but the seller keeps making it hard. After weeks of trying hard, we finally could make the down payment and waited until January 8, when was the due date for the first payment to the bank. But, we weren‚Äôt informed about how we could make the payment because Pacific Honda was in communication with Capital One. When we called to have information about the payment process, we learned that Pacific Honda didn‚Äôt send the deal to Capital One on time, so the offer had expired.
- As we mentioned above, we specifically chose Pacific Honda based on their experience because we needed assistance through the process as a first-time purchaser. We believe, all the misfortune we had was based on a lack of knowledge or communication between the departments. Information given or action taken by a department was rejected by another department while we were never informed properly about what was the next. When we wanted to return the car, they said we cannot give it back but Honda can take it back if necessary. The amount of stress and unknown we had made us regret this purchase. Almost after 3 months, we could finalize the process by making the first payment in January and decided to write this feedback.
- We understand problems may occur during a sales process, which is okay. What we care is the way it‚Äôs handled and if the company is solution-oriented. Unfortunately, we couldn‚Äôt see this effort and the lack of communication within the company caused us a lot of time and stress. We are writing this feedback by hoping no one else has the same experience we had.

<Text>UPDATE: As of 01/21/20 I still have not heard back from anyone at Pacific Honda regarding either of my issues. Someone left a message below, saying to contact them, but left no name. When I call the number I get passed around and eventually leave messages for sales managers who have not called me back.

I recently purchased a pre-owned vehicle at Pacific Honda in San Diego. My salesperson, Greg, was excellent. Very accommodating with test drives, vehicle checks, etc. He was not high pressure, so I felt very comfortable with him. Everyone at the facility seemed very nice. So far, I am mostly quite happy with the vehicle, and felt I got it for a decent price.

There are just two reasons I am giving a 3 instead of 4 or 5 stars:

1. There was/is a problem with one of the electric windows. I realize I purchased the vehicle "as is"; but I discovered this problem about 2 days after I brought the vehicle home. I contacted Greg via email, and also mentioned it to a representative (whose name I cannot remember) who had called me a few days later to check in on my experience. No one ever got back to me or offered to look at the window to fix it. It is still a problem, and I can tell it's something electrical with the driver's side control, because from the passenger side it opens and closes fine. But again, I never got a response from Pacific Honda regarding this issue. Sort of makes me feel that once the transaction is done, they are done with you.

2. I just recently received a notice in the mail that they ran a credit check/report on me. I paid CASH for this car; so there was absolutely no reason to run my credit. It's no big deal, but it just shouldn't be done. Depending on who you talk to this activity can lower your score. I know of no benefit Pacific Honda would gain from doing this; but who knows? All I know is that they did run an unauthorized credit check. I called the number on the notification letter who said they would pass a message on to the dealership. I want to request they take that activity off my credit history. I have never heard back from anyone at Pacific Honda.

They have a good selection of new and used cars. And again, Greg was great and they were all very nice. However, because of the two issues above, I am doubtful I would go back to them or recommend them.

Update: You left a number in your response but not a name. Who should I ask for?< /Text>< user>

<Review>UPDATE: As of 01/21/20 I still have not heard back from anyone at Pacific Honda regarding either of my issues. Someone left a message below, saying to contact them, but left no name. I recently purchased a pre-owned vehicle at Pacific Honda in San Diego. My salesperson, Greg, was excellent. Very accommodating with test drives, vehicle checks, etc. He was not high pressure, so I felt very comfortable with him. Everyone at the facility seemed very nice. So far, I am mostly quite happy with the vehicle, and felt I got it for a decent price.

There are just two reasons I am giving a 3 instead of 4 or 5 stars:

1. There was/is a problem with one of the electric windows. I realize I purchased the vehicle "as is"; but I discovered this problem about 2 days after I brought the vehicle home. I contacted Greg via email, and also mentioned it to a representative (whose name I cannot remember) who had called me a few days later to check in on my experience. No one ever got back to me or offered to look at the window to fix it. It is still a problem, and I can tell it's something electrical with the driver's side control, because from the passenger side it opens and closes fine. But again, I never got a response from Pacific Honda regarding this issue. Sort of makes me feel that once the transaction is done, they are done with you.

2. I just recently received a notice in the mail that they ran a credit check/report on me. I paid CASH for this car; so there was absolutely no reason to run my credit. All I know is that they did run an unauthorized credit check. I called the number on the notification letter who said they would pass a message on to the dealership. I want to request they take that activity off my credit history. I have never heard back from anyone at Pacific Honda.

They have a good selection of new and used cars. And again, Greg was great and they were all very nice. However, because of the two issues above, I am doubtful I would go back to them or recommend them.

< text>
The people who helped me out, individually, were each amazing (Samantha H, Dario, and Scott, specifically, but I also dealt with other employees as well). Scott helped me with finding the right car for me, and went over the features of the cars and how they fit me. Dario helped me with getting my credit approved, which wasn't easy, given what my credit is. Samantha went over the paperwork with me, and made sure I understood all the options I had for the car and all the other details (security features, what happens at the end of my lease, etc).

However, the most frustrating part about my experience was the poor communication, or lack thereof. I had to give my information (address, contact info, income, references) multiple times to different people. After about 4 times giving my info, Dario finally managed to get a deal that I could agree to. Additionally, after I was approved, I received little instruction on what to do next. I was not told what information I would need to bring in, which led to a last minute scramble to find it all in time (which I still didn't).

Despite these frustrating periods, my overall experience was positive. I got a great car that I love for a payment that's good for me. Now I guess I just need to wait until I need service on the car to see how that branch of Pacific Honda handles.</text>

< text>
I bought a new car here -- 2013 Accord Coupe -- I feel that I got a good deal because it was one of the last 2013s on the lot.

Pros:

--My salesman Scott was very nice and not too high pressure.
--There was a small scratch on the back bumper. They took care of it (I think maybe they repainted the bumper) and even put me in a rental car overnight for free.
--The service advisor was very pleasant to deal with.

Cons:

--My biggest problem was dealing with the F&I (Finance and Insurance) person. There was a very high-pressure pitch to buy:
--extended warranty (she made it sound like my Accord would blow up the day after the factory warranty expired...I didn't know that Honda made such junky cars)
--maintenance plan
--door ding plan (no kidding)
--Lo-Jack
--window VIN etching

Even though I said "no" several times, the pressure continued throughout the pitch. It was not a pleasant experience.

--As I mentioned, they needed to keep the car overnight, and gave me a free rental, which was nice, but when I picked it up the next morning it was covered with water drops from being outside overnight. I had just washed and waxed the car and was not happy about this.

An observation, not sure if it's a pro or con:
--The service department was very, very busy when I only the car there to get the bumper scratch repaired. Although they seemed pretty efficient, I would have a little concern about getting work done there on a regular basis. Maybe they're busy because they're good, or it could be that they have a central location in San Diego.<//text>

< Review>
Service could be much better!  Took my CR-V into the Express Oil Center the other day because I am trying to do all of my service at the dealer, and also because I've had bad experiences at Jiffy Lube in the past. The policies and management appears to have changed at Pacific Honda as all cars must not line up at their main service center, even if they are just coming in for an oil change. This seemed a bit ridiculous to me (and many other customers waiting in line) because we had to pull our cars into the main service garage, only to have them moved over to the express garage by the employees. It would have made more sense to do it the old way, i.e. let the express customers wait in line at the express center. To me, this seems like a very poor management decision. I arrived at 6:40 AM (they open at 7 and was second in line. My car wasn't over to the express center until ~7:10 am and my oil change and tire rotation took about 45 minutes. As usual, they tried to get me to pay $55 for a cabin air filter (these cost less than $10 and take 3 seconds to replace or clean out). I find it a bit insulting and unprofessional that they try to upset customers on things like this. However, I don't have much choice as to where I get my oil change, so I'll probably have to keep going back here. Hopefully, management will get their act together by my next oil change.< /Review>

< review>
I had been thinking about a buying a car for some time, but I tend to procrastinate.  I searched the internet, and decided on a Honda Civic.  I was visiting my son in San Diego, and we decided to just go out to look, and maybe test drive a Civic sedan.  When we got to Honda Pacific, which my son chose because of its excellent reviews, we were greeted by Angelina James.  I told her exactly what I was looking for, down to the color, and she asked us to give her a minute.  Almost immediately, she drove the exact car I mentioned, to where we were standing. I decided to test drive the car. It was everything I wanted, but I still wasn't sure I wanted to buy the car that day. Angelina was very professional, not pushy, and explained everything.  She was very personable, and easy to talk with.  I ultimately decided to buy the car.  After all of the paperwork was completed, Angelina spent a long time helping me to understand the phone, navigation system, and other parts of the car.  She acted like she valued me as a customer, even after the car was signed, sealed and delivered.  She did a follow-up call to see how I liked the car, and to thank me for buying it.  I had a very pleasant experience, which was much shorter that I anticipated - from start to finish. I highly recommend Angelina James, and if I were to give her a grade it would be an A+. I would not hesitate to send a friend to Pacific Honda, and I would recommend that they ask for Angelina James.<//review>

I went pacific Honda over the weekend because my check engine light was on. When I got there, their express service had a 2.5 hr line. Fair enough, they have no control over how busy they get, although they could have set up an appointment process. I went to the regular service counter after that and asked what the code in my car meant, and they said that it was the 60K service and that to do that it would cost me $495, I mentioned that I had done my 30K in Oregon and that I don't seem to recall it having cost that much money. They claimed differences in markets, cost of living, etc.

I called my Oregon Honda dealership, and they said that the 60K service cost was $189. I can understand cost of living differences, but $450 vs $189???? really?? so I then decided to call a few other dealers around California, and another one in San Diego charges $270, so I went back in to talk to the service manager and asked why the difference. His answer "I don't know what to tell you!"

I have always had a great experience with Honda dealerships until I got to this one. I'm not exactly sure how Honda Corporation allows this to happen, but they have lost me as a costumer, and I hope they lose many other customers they are trying to cheat out of their rightfully earned money.< /text>

< text>
A week ago my wonderful father checked the tire pressure in my car. He confused my car with my sisters and thought my tires had too much air in them so he let some air out of each. As i pulled away, the "tire pressure" notification came on. So I pulled over, checked the tire pressure of each with my tire gauge and realized what had happened. I had the irritating tire pressure notification in my car for a week and I couldn't for the life of me figure out how to make it go away. I read the manual and was just struggling. So I thought "I'll just pop into the Honda store and ask someone to guide me." When I arrived, a guy walked up to me and asked me the problem. He told me there was "no way to change the notification" and that I had to get my car inspected. I understand the liability of Honda's to need to check each of my tires before I leave the service lot (obviously.) But he continued to repeat "I'm sure the real problem is that the tires really don't have the accurate amount of air in them" insinuating that I really don't know how to check my own tires. Mind you, I'm a 25-year-old female and I get the "pity" and "incompetent" look from people like him often. I explained to him that I had checked multiple times and I can guarantee that It isn't the tire pressure that's the issue. He wasn't convinced and even chucked at my confidence.

I did some more research and I was able to google a resolution. Low and behold, the notification went away in just a few moments.

I went pacific Honda over the weekend because my check engine light was on. When I got there, their express service had a 2.5 hr line. They claimed differences in markets, cost of living, etc.

I have always had a great experience with Honda dealerships until I got to this one. I'm not exactly sure how Honda Corporation allows this to happen, but they have lost me as a costumer, and I hope they lose many other customers they are trying to cheat out of their rightfully earned money.</text>

<Text>I bought a 2015 Honda civic from Pacific Honda in June, 2018. This week when I went to the Pacific Honda Service for a reset in tire pressure checking system, a service guy told me that one of my tire is in different brand with the other three tires. That one is from Yokohama, and the other three are from Michelin, which is the original tire model. I was shocked that this could happen on a car bought from a serious dealership, not from a random guy trying to rip me off. The mismatch in tires is definitely causing different handling in tires due to the material, construction and tread design from different tire manufactuers, and therefore leading to long-term issues in car, such as alignment, suspension and transmission problems.

I went to the Pacific Honda to talk about this and asked for a replacement of the mismatched pair of tires, or at least that one Yokohama tire. The manager, Jose Rogrigues, was trying to convince me that the two mismatched tire are exactly the same without even going out to have a look at my car. He offers to cover only half of the price to replace the Yokohama tire, since it is "not a safety-related issue". How come they can define this is not related to safety? The car parts related to tires could fail earlier than they are supposed to be. When I bought the car, I was told all the tires are new, so I didn't ask if the tires are matched. <Text>I bought a 2015 Honda civic from Pacific Honda in June, 2018. This week when I went to the Pacific Honda Service for a reset in tire pressure checking system, a service guy told me that one of my tire is in different brand with the other three tires. That one is from Yokohama, and the other three are from Michelin, which is the original tire model. I was shocked that this could happen on a car bought from a serious dealership, not from a random guy trying to rip me off. The mismatch in tires is definitely causing different handling in tires due to the material, construction and tread design from different tire manufactuers, and therefore leading to long-term issues in car, such as alignment, suspension and transmission problems.

I went to the Pacific Honda to talk about this and asked for a replacement of the mismatched pair of tires, or at least that one Yokohama tire. The manager, Jose Rogrigues, was trying to convince me that the two mismatched tire are exactly the same without even going out to have a look at my car. He offers to cover only half of the price to replace the Yokohama tire, since it is "not a safety-related issue". How come they can define this is not related to safety? The car parts related to tires could fail earlier than they are supposed to be. When I bought the car, I was told all the tires are new, so I didn't ask if the tires are matched. Aren't the tires supposed to be MATCHED on a car? Another manager, Curtis Ringle, performed a "I have asked my boss and this is the best we can do" act. This is really annoying and disappointing. I am writing this down to let people know never go to Pacific Honda for used car shopping. They will only treat you well before you buy a car from them.< /Text><Rating>1<//Rating></record></dataset><record>

<Rate>5<//Rate><Name>Jason Schafer< /Name><Pics>None<//Pics>< Text>
I have to admit that I get a stomach ache when I usually walk onto a car dealership lot. I love cars.  I used to go with my dad and test drive cars for fun as a kid, but I get uncomfortable with the high-pressure sales the usually comes with walking onto a dealer lot.  Pacific Honda was a completely different, and wonderfully refreshing experience.  I don't do a lot of online reviews, but after reading a previous scathing review, I feel like I need to tell my wonderfully positive experience.  I'm also going to post this on yelp.  This place deserves some kudos and cookies.  I had a pretty good idea what kind of car and model I wanted, the Pilot Touring.  Marcos was informative, friendly, and helpful.  I NEVER felt pressured.  When it came time to talk about price, he and Paul (the sales manager) were open and fair.  Paul was clear about what he had available, what discounts he could give (and couldn't) and what he was willing to do. I'd done my research, so I knew what I could afford and what was a fair price.  I hate haggling, back-n-forth negotiation stuff.  I want to treat people with respect and fairness and I want to be treated the same.   We agreed on a fair price, a great price.  I don't make purchases like this without talking it over with my wife (duh!).  They never flinched when I told them I would talk about it that night and call them in the morning. I'd been to 3 other dealerships (Toyota and Honda) and ALWAYS got pressured to make a purchase that day.  Paul encouraged me to make the best decision for me and my family.  When I went back the next day, Paul and Tony were great. (Marcos was out, but he connected us with Tony who answered every question.)  It was the Dec 31st, so Paul was slammed with everybody else trying to get a purchase done before the end of the year stuff, but he STILL made the effort to come talk to us 3-4 times and check in.  I know they are trying to sell cars, but he could have sat in his office. Instead, he took a moment to make sure that we were happy.  My parents purchased a CRV from Pacific Honda, and we got the Pilot we wanted for a price I would have had to fight to get at another dealership. I walked out feeling positive, happy, and relaxed (not pressured and defensive like other dealerships).  I would HIGHLY recommend you go and talk to them if you are in the market for a new car.< /Text>

<Review>Came to Pacific Honda to buy a brand new car for my mom and was greeted as soon as we pulled up by Jon our salesman. He instantly put us at ease and we did not feel pressured at all to buy a car. Jon was very straightforward, helpful, and came of fas sincere in trying to help my mom find a car that she really liked. After a couple of test drives, my mom settled on a 2012 brownish/grey Honda Civic. The easy part was finding the car, now the real fun begins.

Being in auto finance has given me an inside perspective on buying a car. Never settle for the MSRP price on a new car and if you aren't at some point getting up out of your seat to walk out of the dealership then you haven't negotiated hard enough.

Well, I was pleasantly surprised with how things worked out. Jon gave me the invoice price of the vehicle and even worked out a deal for us on the alarm. Although the interest rate was unappealing at first, Jon was able to work with the finance manager to get the rate adjusted and an even further price discount on the car! Amazing! I didn't think it was possible for me to feel so at ease, but Jon made every effort to make this transaction pleasant!

My mom is happy with her new car, the financing, and the way we were treated by Jon at this dealership. As long as Pacific Honda has Jon as a salesman, we will back again for the 2013 Honda Accord when I am ready to buy!

What ever happened to customer service? Let me make sure when you read this review you will understand why I'm frustrated and disappointed. The whole experience could have been fantastic review. Here's why...
My Partner and I bought a 2012 Honda Civic LX brand new. Upon getting financed we already knew our finance rate was going to be higher than previously purchased Honda's from the same dealership because of some financial setbacks from 2 years prior. He had to get a car for work reasons and we didn't want some other used car with problems from a previous owner. So the sales person gave us a 17% interest rate which was not negotiable. Again it is what it is. It didn't matter we had bought 2 other brand new Honda's from Pacific Honda. They put my name as the buyer his name as the co-maker. We caught that and that was supposed to have been changed. We got every excuse from it was the bank who did that to they lost the paperwork and so on. Finally after 8 months it appears the names are corrected. He is the legal owner and I the co-signer. Now normally a co-signer does not get monthly bills unless there is a problem with the owner. Up until the last 4-6 months I have received a monthly bill and he sometimes never got one.
He has been paying 17% interest and still is and the dealership has gotten a kick back from Chase Bank for bringing us the customer to them. The amount that gets applied to the principle each month ranges from $175-$200. Our car payment is $423.00 per month. The bank and the dealership are getting more than $225 per month in interest. Now we've all heard of being ripped off but this is what I call getting the screws put to you with a smile. Any reputable business that is truly into customer service and would like a customer to be happy wouldn't do this. We knew the interest was going to be higher before going the Honda dealership but not that high. Pacific Honda is not a buy here pay here tiny dealership or car lot, they are one of the biggest Honda dealerships on the West Coast part of another parent company even larger.
So I would be very careful about buying your next car from this dealership. There has been many times we had little to eat because of struggling to pay them and all the other bills that you have in life.
The service department never answers their phone it's all voicemail. You sit on hold and then get transferred to reservations just to book service. The service advisors will not call you back and more than not the items needed fixed on the car are never done the same day because they need more time. Now remember he dropped his car off at 8-9am they have it all day, he gets a rental pays for the rental and then at 6pm comes back thinking the repairs are going to be done and they aren't. They tell you when you leave the car that they will have everything repaired when you leave it, then it's we got too busy and we had other cars that got done before yours. Why have a reservation and be told one thing then take in more cars than they can fix so that we have to come back pay for a rental car again. At least 1 time the car still had to come back a 3rd time. We have owned 4 Honda's, 2 BMW's, 2 Toyota's  and have never been treated as rude as Pacific Honda's service dept. does to it's customers. I've watched more customers than I can count on 1 hand be so frustrated they were screaming at the cashier or service advisors when picking up their cars. The response from the Honda reps., is like "Oh well" next customer... We urge you to think about where your hard earned cash is going to go and spend it with another dealership that earns your business. We've all heard this "they got your money now and your screwed" don't let that be you.< /text>

<rating>5<//rating><Review>On January 31 we purchased a new 2018 Honda Civic EX from Pacific Honda. And we have Yvon Serov to thank for that. We were searching for a ‚Äúnew" car for my daughter who was looking to replace her 2003 Honda Civic. Initially my daughter planned to purchase a previously owned vehicle because that would fit better into her current financial situation. In addition to Honda Civics and Accords, we also researched Toyota Corollas and Camrys, Mazda 3s, Hyundai Elantras, Subaru Imprezas, Chevy Cruzes, plus Ford Focuses and Fusions.  After all that research, we determined that a Honda Civic was the best in class for the vehicles that my daughter was interested in and could best afford. Thus, we first met Yvon because of my daughter's interest in a 2016 Honda Civic EX that Pacific Honda was offering for sale.

My daughter was able to successfully communicate with Yvon independently of myself and I believe that when Yvon learned that my daughter was also researching new 2018 Honda Civics, he and she began discussing what Pacific Honda could do to compete with other Honda dealerships' best offers. Truthfully I felt somewhat of an obligation with the staff who had been very kind and patient with us taking time and negotiating the best deal to date. So if the offers had been comparable, I would have felt that the other dealership deserved our business. However, when Yvon informed us that Pacific Honda was able to offer an even better price by a few hundred dollars, we were happy to listen.

When the three of us met together, my daughter and I found Yvon to be honest with us and not try to up sell us. < Review>
What ever happened to customer service? Let me make sure when you read this review you will understand why I'm frustrated and disappointed. The whole experience could have been fantastic review. Here's why...
My Partner and I bought a 2012 Honda Civic LX brand new. Upon getting financed we already knew our finance rate was going to be higher than previously purchased Honda's from the same dealership because of some financial setbacks from 2 years prior. He had to get a car for work reasons and we didn't want some other used car with problems from a previous owner. So the sales person gave us a 17% interest rate which was not negotiable. Again it is what it is. It didn't matter we had bought 2 other brand new Honda's from Pacific Honda. They put my name as the buyer his name as the co-maker. We caught that and that was supposed to have been changed. We got every excuse from it was the bank who did that to they lost the paperwork and so on. Finally after 8 months it appears the names are corrected. He is the legal owner and I the co-signer. Now normally a co-signer does not get monthly bills unless there is a problem with the owner. Up until the last 4-6 months I have received a monthly bill and he sometimes never got one.
He has been paying 17% interest and still is and the dealership has gotten a kick back from Chase Bank for bringing us the customer to them. The amount that gets applied to the principle each month ranges from $175-$200. Our car payment is $423.00 per month. The bank and the dealership are getting more than $225 per month in interest. Now we've all heard of being ripped off but this is what I call getting the screws put to you with a smile. Any reputable business that is truly into customer service and would like a customer to be happy wouldn't do this. We knew the interest was going to be higher before going the Honda dealership but not that high. Pacific Honda is not a buy here pay here tiny dealership or car lot, they are one of the biggest Honda dealerships on the West Coast part of another parent company even larger.
So I would be very careful about buying your next car from this dealership. There has been many times we had little to eat because of struggling to pay them and all the other bills that you have in life.
The service department never answers their phone it's all voicemail. You sit on hold and then get transferred to reservations just to book service. The service advisors will not call you back and more than not the items needed fixed on the car are never done the same day because they need more time. Now remember he dropped his car off at 8-9am they have it all day, he gets a rental pays for the rental and then at 6pm comes back thinking the repairs are going to be done and they aren't. They tell you when you leave the car that they will have everything repaired when you leave it, then it's we got too busy and we had other cars that got done before yours. Why have a reservation and be told one thing then take in more cars than they can fix so that we have to come back pay for a rental car again. At least 1 time the car still had to come back a 3rd time. We have owned 4 Honda's, 2 BMW's, 2 Toyota's  and have never been treated as rude as Pacific Honda's service dept. does to it's customers. I've watched more customers than I can count on 1 hand be so frustrated they were screaming at the cashier or service advisors when picking up their cars. The response from the Honda reps., is like "Oh well" next customer... We urge you to think about where your hard earned cash is going to go and spend it with another dealership that earns your business. We've all heard this "they got your money now and your screwed" don't let that be you.<//Review>

<review>My recent experience with Pacific Honda was exceptional.  For real.

First off, I had done quite a bit of independent research in advance.  This involved discussions with industry-knowledgeable friends, family and co-workers - plus poring over YouTube videos and articles/research/opinions of strangers on the internet.  All of this preliminary groundwork led me to leaning very heavily toward a 2017 Honda Civic.  However, there were about five different options - each quite distinguishable from the others.  And because it is best for one to gather information in order to make an informed decision - it was clear that some further investigating along the front lines had to be done.

Thus, "armed" with my "independent research," I set out for the dealerships.

Not long into that first day of groundwork at the dealerships, my Sales Consultant at Pacific Honda turned out to be Jimmy Gardemann.  That would prove to be quite the lucky break right there.

And because though my research had me "pre-sold" on a Honda (and almost certainly a 2017 Civic), I had not then yet made up my mind on what pro/con blend of features and accessories that I would ultimately opt for.   And in all of these analyses, every positive aspect of a vehicle is counter-balanced to some degree or another by cost/price considerations.

Well, Jimmy really helped out with all that --- as he patiently, candidly and knowledgeably fielded all of my questions (and there were a lot of them).  In other instances, in a no pressure very relaxed manner - he would articulate the various pros, cons and relevant considerations. All of this here was key.  And as Jimmy can also attest, I took copious notes throughout this process - as this was a major decision not to be taken lightly.

All of these visits to the dealers took a full Saturday and Sunday (from open to close each day).  And over that span, I tried pretty much every Honda dealer in San Diego County - all in furtherance of the singular purpose of getting the car I wanted at the best price.  As I continued to negotiate for the best deal, I paid visits to a few of the dealerships more than once.

Long story short:  I got a truly fantastic deal at Pacific Honda (that was unmatchable by the nearest competitors).  Additionally, Jimmy has been absolutely wonderful since our first point of contact on the morning of the 24th right on through to the present day.  In fact, this "post-purchase" level of customer service struck me as particularly remarkable - and further inspired me to write up a review to share my thoughts on Jimmy Gardemann.

Some salespeople have a tendency to pretend to be nice - but Jimmy is the genuine article, the "real McCoy" so to speak.  He's just a legit nice guy that happens to be a straight shooter that is easy to talk to - and one who can shed a lot of light on matters acutely relevant to the Honda car-buying experience.

Summing up the final scorecard:  I landed an awesome car at an unbeatable price with remarkably strong customer service.  More specifically, I hooked a 2017 Honda Civic Hatchback Sport Touring at what I personally verified to be the best price in San Diego - and the customer service at Pacific Honda gets an A+++, from Jimmy to "Sam" (Samantha H.) to Steve and J.R.

And if anyone is looking for a fair, honest and likable car salesperson - with which to discuss the purchase of a Honda (awesome cars by the way), I would urge them to specifically ask for Jimmy Gardemann at Pacific Honda.  [And then feel free to negotiate the heck out of the price - because everybody wants to arrive at a deal that they feel really good about.]< /review>< Pics>

This dealear does not know what a customer service is. Especially the so called "manager" named Paul and Salesperson Robby. After buying the Odyssey at this dealer, I referred my friend's family who was also looking into buying the same vehicle. When they went and told Robby that their friend(me) bought the vehicle at x amount, the Salesperson did not believe them and accused them of lying. My friends felt very disrespected and mistreated by this salesperson and the manager. So I went with my friends to the dealer the next day to prove that I was the friend who bought the vehicle there the week before. My friend's couple and me and husband were not even welcomed. Paul the manager came out at the door said he was not willing to make any offer. He lied by saying that his salesperson spent the whole day with my friends trying to negotiate the price when it was only for an hour. The manager was NOT willing to hear any of my friends had to say and only believed what his salesperson told him. Paul did make a ridiculous offer saying that my friends would have to pay $400 more if they wanted to buy the vehicle. When I complained that this was not what I had expected for my friends to be treated, the manager didn't care. He said there were eight other Honda dealers in San Diego that my friends could go to. This so called manager didn't even seem to care whether I go on all the car sites and yelp leaving negative comments. He said I could go and complain all I wanted. This dealer is full of crap and disrespect for customers!!! And you know this dealer had the guts to call my friends that evening saying that they were willing to make the offer. Who in the world want to go back to the same dealer that treated like you a piece of s*** and not welcomed into the dealer would go back and buy the car. That was even more humiliating and disgusting getting a call back from the dealer. I still get very upset and infurious when I think about the treatment that my friends and I received at this dealer.

My message to the Pacific Honda General Manager, hire a private consultant and reexamine how your managers and salespersons are treating customers.  If you want to continue to have customers being disrespected, mistreated, humiliated and disgusted by your staff, please don't do anything.  Customers are not STUPID and they will do their homework and go to EIGHT OTHER HONDA DEALERS just like your manager Paul said.

If you are in San Diego and looking to buy a Honda, The BOTTOM LINE, DON't go to Pacific Honda< /Text>
